            [
                'name'        => 'Rat Guard',
                'category'    => 'Marine Safety',
                'image'       => '/images/products/rat-guard.png',
                'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>Marine Rat Guard. Essential Rodent Barrier for Mooring Lines and Vessel Protection While Docked.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>Marine Rat Guard</strong> is an essential vessel protection device fitted to mooring lines and ropes to prevent rats and rodents from boarding ships while berthed at port. Typically <strong>conical or disc-shaped</strong> and manufactured from durable steel, aluminum, or impact-resistant plastic, the rat guard creates a smooth, angled barrier that rodents cannot grip, climb over, or circumvent — blocking their primary access route to the vessel via mooring lines. Rat guards protect cargo integrity, prevent damage to wiring and stores, and critically block the <strong>transmission of rodent-borne diseases</strong> to crew, passengers, and cargo.</p><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Key Features</h2><ul class="mb-12 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Conical / Disc Barrier Design:</strong> Angled smooth surface creates a physical barrier rodents cannot grip or climb — the geometry forces any rat attempting to cross the guard to lose footing and fall back to the dock</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Durable Materials:</strong> Available in steel, aluminum, or heavy-duty plastic — all resistant to the corrosion, UV exposure, and physical wear of a mooring environment</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Disease Prevention:</strong> Blocks rodents from boarding and contaminating cargo, provisions, and accommodation spaces — preventing transmission of leptospirosis, salmonella, and other rodent-borne pathogens</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Cargo & Wiring Protection:</strong> Prevents rodent gnawing damage to electrical wiring, hydraulic lines, insulation, packaging, and stored cargo — protecting against costly damage and fire risk</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Easy Fitting:</strong> Simple installation onto any mooring line or rope without specialist tools — can be fitted and removed quickly during berthing and departure operations</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Port Health Compliance:</strong> Required by port health authorities and vessel inspection regimes worldwide as a condition of safe port entry and food safety compliance</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">📋 Usage Note</strong>Rat guards must be fitted to <strong>all mooring lines, shore power cables, and gangway ropes</strong> whenever the vessel is berthed at port. Guards should be positioned as far from the vessel side as practical to maximize the drop distance for any rodent attempting to cross. Inspect guards regularly for damage or bypassing and replace any unit showing cracks, deformation, or corrosion.</div>',
