               'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>Life Raft Oar. Collapsible Emergency Paddle for Life Raft Maneuvering and Survival Navigation.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>Marine Life Raft Oar</strong> is a lightweight, collapsible paddle designed for manual propulsion and steering of life rafts and inflatable survival craft during emergency situations at sea. Featuring a <strong>high-visibility orange blade</strong> with an anodized aluminum telescoping shaft, this oar provides survivors with the means to maneuver away from hazards, paddle toward rescue vessels, maintain position in currents, and steer the raft in the intended direction of survival drift. Its collapsible two-section design allows for compact storage within life raft survival kits while extending to a functional full-length paddle when deployed. A standard item included in <strong>SOLAS Pack A and Pack B</strong> life raft survival kits.</p><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Primary Functions</h2><div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-12"><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">🚣</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Manual Propulsion</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Enables survivors to manually paddle the life raft toward rescue vessels, shorelines, or away from hazards such as oil spills, ship wreckage, or dangerous currents. Provides a means of controlled movement independent of wind or current direction.</p></div><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">🧭</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Steering & Positioning</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Used as a rudder to maintain heading and correct the orientation of the life raft relative to waves, wind, and approaching rescue craft. Effective steering reduces broaching risk and allows survivors to present the most visible profile to rescuers.</p></div></div><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Key Features</h2><ul class="mb-12 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">SOLAS Compliant:</strong> Meets international maritime survival equipment regulations as a standard propulsion item in SOLAS Pack A and Pack B life raft survival kits</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Collapsible Two-Section Design:</strong> Aluminum shaft separates into two sections for compact storage and reassembles quickly into a full-length functional oar without tools or technical knowledge</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">High-Visibility Orange Blade:</strong> Bright orange paddle blade maximizes visibility above the waterline, doubling as a secondary visual signal to attract the attention of passing rescue aircraft and vessels</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Lightweight Aluminum Shaft:</strong> Anodized aluminum tube construction provides the strength needed for effective paddling while keeping overall oar weight minimal for fatigued survivors</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Retention Hook End Cap:</strong> Hook-shaped end cap on the handle allows the oar to be secured to the life raft lifeline, preventing loss overboard during use in rough sea conditions</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Corrosion Resistant:</strong> All materials are selected for resistance to saltwater corrosion and UV degradation, maintaining structural integrity and functionality throughout extended storage and emergency use</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Tip</strong>Inspect the oar blade, shaft sections, and locking collar during <strong>annual life raft servicing</strong> for cracks, corrosion, or joint looseness that could cause failure under paddling loads. Check that the two shaft sections lock together securely with no play or rotation. Rinse thoroughly with fresh water after any saltwater exposure and dry before restowing. Replace immediately if the blade shows cracking, the shaft is bent or corroded, or the section locking mechanism fails to hold firmly under pressure.</div>',
