rong> Certified minimum light output meets international visibility requirements, ensuring the signal is detectable at operationally effective range by rescue vessels and aircraft in darkness and adverse weather conditions</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">3-Year Service Validity:</strong> The sealed seawater battery cell remains fully operational for 3 years from manufacture date without requiring charging, testing, or battery replacement during normal storage — simplifying maintenance scheduling</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">CCS Certified:</strong> Certified under China Classification Society (CCS) or equivalent qualification standards, confirming full compliance with international maritime survivor location light safety and performance requirements</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Tip</strong>Check the manufacture date and validity label during every <strong>annual life jacket or immersion suit servicing</strong> and replace the light unit immediately upon reaching its <strong>3-year validity expiry date</strong>. Inspect the light body, lens, and seawater activation ports for salt crystal blockage, corrosion, or physical cracking that could impede seawater contact with the battery cell or reduce light output. Keep the seawater activation ports clear and unobstructed at all times — do not apply tape, grease, or coatings over the activation openings. Store in a dry location attached to the life jacket away from freshwater exposure, as premature contact with any water source may partially activate the battery and reduce available lighting duration.</div>',
