                'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>Embarkation Ladder. SOLAS-Required Safety Ladder for Lifeboat, Rescue Craft, and Emergency Evacuation Access.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>Embarkation Ladder</strong> is a critical SOLAS-required marine safety device providing safe, stable access between the vessel\'s embarkation deck and a lifeboat, rescue craft, or water surface during emergency evacuation, crew transfer, or rescue operations. Constructed from durable, weather-resistant materials with non-slip steps and a rigid, stable structure, the embarkation ladder ensures secure footing for persons descending under emergency conditions — including in rough sea conditions, at night, or when fatigued. The embarkation ladder is a mandatory item under <strong>SOLAS Chapter III</strong> and must be maintained in a state of immediate readiness at all times.</p><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Key Features</h2><ul class="mb-12 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">SOLAS Chapter III Compliant:</strong> Meets all mandatory requirements for embarkation ladder construction, dimensions, and performance under SOLAS for lifeboat and rescue boat embarkation stations</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Non-Slip Steps:</strong> Step surface designed to provide secure grip for bare feet or wet footwear — reducing the risk of slip and fall during rapid emergency descent</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Weather-Resistant Materials:</strong> UV-stabilized, saltwater-resistant materials maintain strength and flexibility across the full range of marine climate conditions</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Stable Structure:</strong> Ladder construction resists twisting and swinging during use, providing a predictable and stable descent surface even when the vessel is rolling in heavy weather</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Emergency Ready:</strong> Designed for immediate deployment without tools or complex rigging — ensuring the ladder can be in service within seconds of an emergency being declared</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Note</strong>Inspect the embarkation ladder at each <strong>monthly safety inspection</strong> and before every lifeboat drill. Check for UV degradation, rope fraying, step cracking, lashing integrity, and securing point condition. The ladder must be stowed ready for immediate deployment at the embarkation station and must reach the waterline with the vessel at its lightest load line.</div>',
