ssure Rated Construction:</strong> Adaptor body and both coupling interfaces precision-rated to withstand the full operating and surge pressures of shipboard fire main systems — maintaining complete leak-free integrity under all system pressure conditions without flow restriction or pressure drop across the adaptor body</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Marine Brass or Gunmetal Body:</strong> High-grade marine brass or gunmetal construction provides superior resistance to saltwater corrosion, dezincification, and the thermal and mechanical stresses encountered during active shipboard firefighting operations and long-term marine environment storage</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Compact & Lightweight Design:</strong> Compact adaptor form factor allows efficient storage within hydrant cabinet enclosures, firefighting equipment lockers, and portable firefighting kit bags without adding significant weight or bulk to the overall firefighting equipment complement</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">SOLAS System Compatible:</strong> Designed and dimensioned for use within SOLAS-compliant shipboard fire main systems and firefighting equipment sets aboard commercial, passenger, and offshore vessels operating under Japanese flag and international registry on global trade routes</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Tip</strong>Inspect the Nakajima fire hose adaptor before each voyage and during <strong>scheduled periodic maintenance</strong> for coupling lug wear, snap-lock mechanism condition and retention force on both coupling ends, body corrosion or pitting, inter