m Compatible:</strong> Designed and dimensioned for use within SOLAS-compliant shipboard fire main systems and firefighting hose assemblies aboard commercial, passenger, and offshore vessels operating under any flag state and international registry on global maritime trade routes</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Tip</strong>Inspect all Storz fire hose couplings before each voyage and during <strong>scheduled periodic maintenance</strong> for locking cam wear and retention force, coupling lug condition, face gasket compression set or cracking, body corrosion or pitting, and hose tail swaging or crimping integrity where the coupling is attached to the hose body. After each use or saltwater exposure, flush all couplings thoroughly with fresh water to remove salt deposits from the locking cam mechanism, lug faces, and internal waterway. Apply a light coat of approved silicone grease to the locking cams, coupling lugs, and face gasket after flushing to maintain smooth quarter-turn coupling engagement, prevent cam corrosion seizure, and preserve long-term gasket flexibility and sealing performance. Inspect and replace face gaskets at each annual service or immediately if compression set, cracking, deformation, or pressure leakage at the coupling joint face is detected. Test locking cam retention force during each inspection — cams that release under light rotational load must be replaced immediately as they present a risk of accidental hose disconnection under operating pressure. Replace any coupling immediately if cam retention is insufficient, lug damage prevents secure engagement, or body corrosion has compromised the structural integrity of the coupling.</div>',
