            [
                'name'        => 'Fireman Axe',
                'category'    => 'Fire & Emergency',
                'image'       => '/images/products/fireman-axe.png',
                'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>Fireman Axe. Heavy-Duty Marine Firefighter Rescue Axe for Shipboard Fire Emergency and Forcible Entry Operations.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>Marine Fireman Axe</strong> is a heavy-duty, purpose-built firefighting hand tool designed for use by shipboard firefighting crews during fire emergency response operations aboard commercial vessels, offshore platforms, and industrial marine facilities. Combining a <strong>sharp cutting blade for forcible entry and ventilation</strong> with a <strong>hardened pick or poll head for breaching, prying, and penetrating</strong> ship structures, the fireman axe is one of the most essential and versatile tools in the marine firefighter\'s equipment arsenal. Constructed from <strong>high-grade forged steel</strong> with a fire-resistant, non-conductive handle, this axe enables firefighting crews to rapidly breach locked doors, bulkheads, and structural panels to gain access to fire-affected compartments, create ventilation openings to release heat and smoke, and perform search and rescue operations in smoke-logged shipboard spaces. A mandatory component of the <strong>SOLAS-compliant marine firefighter personal protective equipment and tools set</strong> carried aboard commercial and passenger vessels worldwide.</p><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Primary Functions</h2><div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-12"><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">🪓</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Forcible Entry & Breaching</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Used to rapidly breach locked or jammed doors, hatches, bulkheads, and structural panels to gain firefighting access to fire-affected compartments — enabling firefighting crews to deliver water and extinguishing agents directly to the seat of the fire without delay when conventional entry routes are blocked or inaccessible.</p></div><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">💨</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Ventilation & Rescue</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Creates ventilation openings in ship structure to release accumulated heat, smoke, and toxic gases from fire-affected compartments — improving visibility and survivability conditions for both firefighting crews and trapped survivors during search and rescue operations in smoke-logged shipboard spaces.</p></div></div><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Key Features</h2><ul class="mb-12 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Forged Steel Axe Head:</strong> High-grade forged steel construction provides the impact strength, edge retention, and structural durability required to breach steel doors, wooden panels, and composite shipboard structures repeatedly under the demanding conditions of emergency firefighting operations</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Dual-Function Head Design:</strong> Sharpened cutting blade on one side for chopping, splitting, and cutting through structural materials combined with a hardened pick or flat poll head on the opposing side for prying, penetrating, and breaching operations — maximizing the operational versatility of a single tool during fire emergency response</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Fire-Resistant Non-Conductive Handle:</strong> Fiberglass, composite, or treated wooden handle provides fire resistance, electrical non-conductivity, and impact shock absorption — protecting the firefighter from electrical hazards in damaged shipboard electrical installations and reducing hand fatigue during prolonged breaching operations</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Corrosion-Resistant Finish:</strong> Protective coating or surface treatment on the axe head provides resistance to saltwater corrosion and oxidation during long-term storage in shipboard firefighting equipment lockers and hydrant cabinet enclosures in marine environments</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Balanced Weight Distribution:</strong> Carefully balanced head and handle weight ratio provides maximum swing force and accurate strike placement while minimizing firefighter fatigue during sustained forcible entry operations in confined shipboard spaces</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">SOLAS PPE Tool Set Compatible:</strong> Dimensioned and specified as a mandatory tool component of the SOLAS-compliant marine firefighter equipment set carried aboard commercial, passenger, and offshore vessels operating under international maritime safety regulations</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Tip</strong>Inspect the fireman axe before each voyage and during <strong>scheduled periodic maintenance</strong> for blade edge sharpness and condition, pick or poll head integrity, handle structural condition, handle-to-head connection security, and protective coating condition on the axe head. After each use or exposure to saltwater, clean the axe head thoroughly with fresh water to remove salt deposits and dry immediately to prevent rust formation on uncoated steel surfaces. Apply a light coat of approved corrosion-inhibiting oil to the axe head after cleaning and drying to maintain surface protection during storage. Inspect the handle for cracks, splits, or looseness at the head connection — a loose or cracked handle presents a serious safety risk during forcible entry operations and must be replaced immediately. Maintain the cutting blade edge with a sharpening stone or file during periodic maintenance to ensure the axe remains capable of effective cutting performance. Store the axe in its designated bracket or locker in a dry, accessible location as part of the complete firefighter PPE set ready for immediate emergency deployment.</div>',
