            [
                'name'        => 'Fireman Suit',
                'category'    => 'Fire & Emergency',
                'image'       => '/images/products/fireman-suit.png',
                'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>Fireman Suit DFXF-93-A. EN 469 Certified Aluminized Heat-Insulation Firefighter Protective Suit for Marine Fire Emergency Operations.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>DFXF-93-A Fireman Suit</strong> is a premium-grade, aluminized structural firefighting protective suit engineered to the rigorous requirements of <strong>EN 469 (2005) including Amendment A1 (2006) and Corrigendum AC (2006)</strong> — the European standard for protective clothing for firefighters. Constructed from <strong>flame-retardant fabric coated with aluminum foil</strong>, this suit combines the radiant heat reflection properties of aluminized outer fabric with the thermal insulation, flame resistance, waterproofing, and mechanical strength required for safe interior and exterior shipboard firefighting operations. The aluminum foil coating reflects the intense radiated heat generated by shipboard fires — dramatically reducing the thermal load on the wearer during fire attack operations in engine rooms, cargo holds, and machinery spaces. With certified performance across heat radiation resistance, flame retardancy, waterproofing, and tearing strength, the DFXF-93-A provides comprehensive full-body protection as the primary outer garment of the <strong>SOLAS-compliant marine firefighter personal protective equipment ensemble</strong>. Certified under <strong>CCS or equivalent qualification standards</strong> for use aboard commercial and passenger vessels operating under international maritime safety regulations.</p><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Material Performance Specifications</h2><div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-12"><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">🌡️</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Heat Radiation Resistance</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Under heat radiation of <strong>10 kW/m²</strong>, the temperature increase on the inner fabric surface does not exceed <strong>25°C after 30 seconds</strong> of continuous irradiation — confirming that the aluminized outer layer and thermal liner effectively limit heat transfer to the wearer\'s body during sustained radiant heat exposure at the intensity levels encountered in active shipboard fire environments.</p></div><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">🔥</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Flame Retardancy</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Flame-retardant fabric achieves a <strong>char length of ≤100 mm</strong> in the 7-second flame retardancy test — confirming that the suit fabric self-extinguishes rapidly after flame removal and does not continue to burn, melt, or drip in a manner that would extend flame contact with the wearer\'s body during brief flame exposure in a fire emergency.</p></div><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">💧</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Waterproof Performance</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Suit fabric achieves a waterproof resistance of <strong>≥4,000 Pa</strong> — preventing water penetration through the suit material during firefighting water application operations, ensuring the wearer remains dry and thermally protected even during sustained exposure to firefighting water streams and spray in wet shipboard firefighting environments.</p></div><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">💪</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Tearing Strength</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Fabric tearing strength of <strong>≥32 N</strong> confirms resistance to tearing and mechanical damage during physically demanding firefighting operations in confined shipboard spaces — maintaining the protective integrity of the suit when subjected to snagging, abrasion, and physical stress against sharp structural elements and equipment during fire attack and rescue operations.</p></div></div><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Key Features</h2><ul class="mb-12 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">EN 469 Certified Construction:</strong> Fully certified to EN 469 (2005) including Amendment A1 (2006) and Corrigendum AC (2006) — the European harmonized standard for heat and flame protective clothing for firefighters, confirming compliance with the most rigorous international structural firefighting protective clothing performance requirements</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Aluminized Flame-Retardant Outer Shell:</strong> Flame-retardant base fabric coated with aluminum foil outer layer provides high-efficiency reflection of radiated heat from fire sources — dramatically reducing the thermal load on the wearer during close-proximity fire attack operations where radiated heat intensity is greatest</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Multi-Layer Thermal Protection System:</strong> Multi-layer suit construction incorporating outer aluminized shell, moisture barrier, and thermal liner layers provides comprehensive protection against heat conduction, radiated heat, steam, and hot liquid splash — maintaining safe inner surface temperatures throughout the rated duration of firefighting exposure</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Full-Body Coverage Design:</strong> Complete suit coverage from wrist to ankle with integrated collar, cuff, and ankle sealing interfaces ensures no gaps in thermal and flame protection between the suit and adjacent PPE components — including helmet neck curtain, firefighter gloves, and rubber boots — when worn as part of the complete firefighter PPE ensemble</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">SCBA & PPE Ensemble Compatible:</strong> Suit dimensions, collar configuration, wrist closure, and overall cut designed for correct fit and unrestricted movement when worn over the complete SOLAS marine firefighter PPE ensemble including self-contained breathing apparatus harness, safety belt, and thermal undergarments</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">CCS Certified:</strong> Certified under China Classification Society (CCS) or equivalent qualification standards, confirming full compliance with international maritime firefighter protective clothing requirements for use aboard commercial, passenger, and offshore vessels</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Tip</strong>Inspect the fireman suit before each voyage and during <strong>scheduled periodic maintenance</strong> for aluminized outer layer delamination or peeling, fabric tears or abrasion damage, seam integrity, closure system operation, moisture barrier condition, and thermal liner compression or damage. After each use or contamination with soot, chemicals, or firefighting agents, clean the suit according to the manufacturer\'s specified cleaning procedure — improper cleaning methods can damage the aluminized coating, flame-retardant treatment, and moisture barrier, reducing protective performance below certified levels. Never use bleach, fabric softeners, or harsh detergents on the suit fabric as these chemically degrade flame-retardant treatments and moisture barrier integrity. Allow the suit to dry completely in a shaded, ventilated area before storage — never dry with direct heat. Any suit that has been subjected to direct flame contact, significant heat exposure, chemical contamination, or physical tearing must be immediately withdrawn from service, professionally inspected, and recertified before return to operational use. Replace the suit at the manufacturer\'s recommended service life interval regardless of apparent visual condition, as thermal and flame protective properties degrade over time with use, cleaning, and UV exposure.</div>',
