                ],
                'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>PS Water Fire Monitor. Heavy-Duty Marine Water Fire Monitor for High-Volume Shipboard and Offshore Fire Suppression Systems.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>PS Water Fire Monitor</strong> is a heavy-duty, fixed or deck-mounted marine firefighting monitor engineered to deliver high-volume water streams at extended range for the suppression of large-scale fires aboard commercial vessels, offshore platforms, tankers, and industrial marine facilities. Designed as a dedicated <strong>water-only fire monitor</strong>, the PS monitor delivers powerful, high-velocity straight water jet streams capable of reaching and suppressing fires across large open deck areas, cargo holds, accommodation block facades, and adjacent vessel or structure surfaces from a fixed installation point — providing a level of water delivery capacity that far exceeds the capability of handheld hose and nozzle firefighting teams. Constructed from <strong>corrosion-resistant marine-grade alloy or stainless steel</strong> with a fully rotatable base, adjustable elevation nozzle, and smooth flow-control valve, the PS Water Fire Monitor is designed for permanent installation at high-risk fire exposure points aboard vessels where rapid, high-volume water application is the primary fire suppression strategy. Designed and manufactured in compliance with <strong>SOLAS regulations and international marine fire protection standards</strong> for installation in fixed fire suppression systems aboard commercial and offshore vessels worldwide.</p><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Primary Functions</h2><div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-12"><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">💧</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">High-Volume Water Fire Attack</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Delivers a high-velocity, high-volume straight water jet stream capable of reaching fires at extended range across large open deck areas, cargo holds, machinery space openings, and adjacent vessel structures — providing the sustained mass water flow rate required for effective suppression of large-scale structural fires that cannot be controlled by handheld firefighting hose teams alone.</p></div><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">🛡️</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Boundary Cooling & Exposure Protection</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Applies continuous high-volume water streams to structural boundaries, bulkheads, deck areas, and adjacent vessel surfaces surrounding an active fire — absorbing radiated and conducted heat to prevent fire spread to adjacent compartments, protect structural integrity, and maintain safe access routes for firefighting crews during sustained shipboard fire emergency operations.</p></div></div><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Key Features</h2><ul class="mb-12 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">High-Volume Water Discharge Capacity:</strong> Large-bore internal waterway and precision-machined nozzle geometry delivers high volumetric water flow rates at the nozzle outlet — providing significantly greater water application rates than handheld hose and nozzle systems for effective suppression of large-scale shipboard fires and sustained boundary cooling operations across wide structural exposure areas</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Full 360-Degree Horizontal Rotation:</strong> Fully rotatable monitor base allows the water discharge stream to be directed across the complete 360-degree horizontal arc from a single fixed installation point — providing maximum fire coverage flexibility across the entire protected deck area, fire zone, or structural exposure boundary without repositioning the monitor or its fire main supply connection</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Adjustable Elevation Nozzle:</strong> Fully adjustable vertical elevation angle from near-horizontal to near-vertical allows the water jet throw angle and landing point to be precisely optimized for the specific fire location, target distance, and prevailing wind conditions — maximizing stream reach accuracy and fire coverage effectiveness during active firefighting operations</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Smooth Flow Control Valve:</strong> Integrated smooth-bore flow control valve allows firefighting crews to open, modulate, and close water flow to the monitor without tools or excessive physical effort — enabling controlled stream startup to prevent hose surge damage, and safe shutdown of water flow after fire suppression without interrupting fire main supply pressure to other firefighting stations</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Corrosion-Resistant Marine Construction:</strong> Monitor body, rotation mechanism, elevation pivot, flow control valve, nozzle, and mounting hardware constructed from marine-grade corrosion-resistant alloy or stainless steel — providing superior resistance to saltwater corrosion, UV degradation, and the mechanical and thermal stresses of active fire suppression operations throughout the full system service life aboard ocean-going vessels</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">SOLAS System Compatible:</strong> Designed and dimensioned for installation in SOLAS-compliant fixed fire suppression systems and fire main distribution networks aboard commercial, passenger, tanker, and offshore vessels — compatible with standard shipboard fire main system operating pressures and hydrant supply connections</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Tip</strong>Inspect the PS Water Fire Monitor before each voyage and during <strong>scheduled periodic maintenance</strong> for horizontal rotation mechanism smoothness and full 360-degree arc operation, elevation adjustment function and locking mechanism security, nozzle orifice condition and blockage, flow control valve operation and seal integrity, body and nozzle corrosion or pitting, and mounting base flange and foundation bolt condition. Operate the monitor through its complete horizontal rotation arc and full elevation range during each maintenance inspection to identify stiffness, binding, or corrosion seizure in the rotation and elevation mechanisms before an emergency deployment — seized mechanisms may prevent correct fire coverage during an actual fire emergency. Flush the monitor body, nozzle, and all internal waterways thoroughly with fresh water after any saltwater exposure and allow to drain completely to prevent internal corrosion from standing water. Apply approved corrosion-inhibiting lubricant to all rotation bearing surfaces, elevation pivot points, and flow control valve stem packing after flushing and draining to maintain smooth operation and prevent saltwater corrosion seizure during the next deployment. Pressure test the monitor and all supply piping flange connections annually at full fire main operating pressure to confirm complete leak-free integrity across all joints and the monitor body. Replace the monitor immediately if rotation mechanism seizure, nozzle damage, flow control valve failure, or mounting base corrosion cannot be fully corrected by approved maintenance procedures.</div>',
            ],
            [
                'name'        => 'Carbon Dioxide (CO2 System)',
                'category'    => 'Fire & Emergency',
                'image'       => '/images/products/co2-system.png',
                'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>Carbon Dioxide (CO2) Fire Suppression System. Fixed Total Flooding CO2 Fire Extinguishing System for Marine Engine Room and Cargo Space Protection.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>Marine Carbon Dioxide (CO2) Fire Suppression System</strong> is a fixed, automatic or manually activated total flooding fire extinguishing system that discharges high-pressure liquid carbon dioxide into a protected enclosed space — rapidly converting to a dense CO2 gas atmosphere that suppresses and extinguishes fire by <strong>reducing the oxygen concentration in the space below the level required to sustain combustion</strong>. As one of the most widely installed and internationally recognized fixed fire suppression systems in marine applications, the CO2 system provides highly effective, electrically non-conductive, and residue-free fire suppression for shipboard spaces where water or foam application would cause unacceptable damage to machinery, electrical equipment, or cargo — including <strong>engine rooms, generator spaces, pump rooms, cargo holds, paint lockers, and other enclosed high-risk spaces</strong>. The system stores CO2 as a pressurized liquid in high-pressure steel cylinders and discharges it through a fixed distribution piping network and discharge nozzles into the protected space upon activation — flooding the entire space volume with CO2 gas to achieve total fire suppression. Designed and manufactured in compliance with <strong>SOLAS Chapter II-2 regulations, IMO MSC circulars, and international marine CO2 system standards</strong> for installation aboard commercial and offshore vessels worldwide, certified under <strong>CCS or equivalent qualification standards.</strong></p><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Primary Functions</h2><div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-12"><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">🔥</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Total Flooding Fire Suppression</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Discharges the calculated CO2 system charge into the protected space within the required discharge time — flooding the entire space volume to a CO2 concentration sufficient to reduce oxygen levels below the combustion threshold, suppressing and extinguishing all fires throughout the space including fires in inaccessible locations, machinery interiors, and bilge areas that cannot be reached by portable extinguishers or hose teams.</p></div><div class="border-2 border-cyan-400 rounded-lg p-5 bg-slate-50"><div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3"><span class="text-2xl">⚙️</span><h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-base m-0">Machinery & Equipment Fire Protection</h3></div><p class="text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Provides fire suppression that leaves no water, foam, or dry powder residue — protecting sensitive machinery, electrical switchboards, generators, pumps, and electronic equipment from secondary damage caused by extinguishing agent contamination, allowing faster post-fire recovery and return to service compared to water or foam suppression alternatives.</p></div></div><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">System Components & Key Features</h2><ul class="mb-12 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">High-Pressure CO2 Cylinder Bank:</strong> System CO2 charge is stored as pressurized liquid in a bank of high-pressure steel cylinders located in a dedicated CO2 room or cabinet — each cylinder hydrostatically tested and certified to the applicable pressure vessel standard, with total cylinder capacity calculated to provide the minimum CO2 flooding concentration required for the protected space volume</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Pilot & Main Cylinder Activation System:</strong> System activation is controlled through a pilot cylinder release mechanism that simultaneously opens the main cylinder bank discharge valves — allowing controlled sequential discharge of the complete CO2 charge into the protected space within the required SOLAS discharge time upon activation from the control cabinet</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Fixed Distribution Piping Network:</strong> Dedicated high-pressure piping network distributes CO2 from the cylinder bank to strategically positioned discharge nozzles throughout the protected space — engineered to deliver uniform CO2 concentration throughout the entire space volume including all machinery interiors, bilge areas, and enclosed sub-spaces within the required discharge time</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Pre-Discharge Alarm & Time Delay:</strong> Mandatory audible and visual pre-discharge alarm system activates before CO2 release to alert all personnel to evacuate the protected space — combined with a time delay mechanism that provides sufficient evacuation time before CO2 discharge commences, preventing personnel from being trapped in the space during flooding</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Manual & Automatic Activation Options:</strong> System can be configured for manual activation from a dedicated control cabinet located outside the protected space, or for automatic activation triggered by fixed fire detection systems — providing operational flexibility while maintaining mandatory pre-discharge alarm and evacuation time delay safety functions in both activation modes</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Space Isolation Integration:</strong> System activation interfaces with ventilation shutdown dampers, fuel supply isolation valves, and machinery shutdown systems to seal the protected space and remove ignition sources before CO2 discharge — maximizing system effectiveness and preventing CO2 dilution through open ventilation openings during flooding</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Electrically Non-Conductive Agent:</strong> Carbon dioxide gas is completely electrically non-conductive — allowing safe discharge into live electrical switchboard rooms, generator spaces, and other spaces with energized electrical equipment without risk of electrical shock to personnel or electrical tracking damage to equipment during or after system discharge</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">SOLAS & CCS Certified:</strong> System design, cylinder capacity, discharge rate, distribution piping, and alarm systems comply with SOLAS Chapter II-2 regulations and are certified under China Classification Society (CCS) or equivalent qualification standards for installation in SOLAS-compliant fixed CO2 fire extinguishing systems aboard commercial and passenger vessels</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-red-50 border-red-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-red-700 mb-1">⚠️ Critical Safety Warning</strong>Carbon dioxide is an odorless, colorless gas that is immediately dangerous to life at the concentrations used for fire suppression. A CO2 system discharge into an occupied space will rapidly cause loss of consciousness and death by asphyxiation. <strong>Never enter a space that has received a CO2 discharge without confirmed atmosphere testing and appropriate respiratory protection.</strong> All personnel must be evacuated from the protected space and all adjacent spaces before system activation. Post evacuation warning signs at all protected space entries after discharge and before re-entry clearance is confirmed by atmosphere testing.</div><div class="mt-6 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">🔧 Maintenance Tip</strong>The CO2 fire suppression system must be inspected and maintained at intervals specified by the manufacturer, flag state requirements, and <strong>SOLAS annual survey requirements</strong>. Annual maintenance must include: CO2 cylinder weight verification against the stamped filled weight to confirm no gas loss, pilot cylinder condition and charge verification, all valve and selector valve operation checks, distribution piping and nozzle integrity inspection and pressure test, pre-discharge alarm and time delay function test, space isolation damper and machinery shutdown interface operation test, and control cabinet condition and labeling inspection. CO2 cylinders that have lost more than the manufacturer\'s permitted weight tolerance must be recharged or replaced immediately. Engage a certified marine CO2 system service provider for all cylinder recharging, valve maintenance, and SOLAS survey certification — never attempt to recharge, repair, or modify CO2 cylinders or high-pressure system components without appropriate certification and equipment.</div>',
            ],

