            [
                'name'        => 'Marine Safety Signs and IMO Symbol',
                'category'    => 'Navigation & Instruments',
                'image'       => '/images/products/imo-symbol.png',
                'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>Marine Safety Signs and IMO Symbols. Standardized IMO Safety Signage for Vessel Wayfinding, Emergency Guidance, and SOLAS Compliance.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>Marine Safety Signs and IMO Symbols</strong> are internationally standardized safety signs designed to communicate critical safety information, emergency exit routes, and life-saving appliance locations to crew and passengers aboard vessels — regardless of language or nationality. Published by the International Maritime Organization (IMO) under the ISM Code and SOLAS Chapter III, these symbols are universally recognized across all flag states and must be posted at muster stations, life jacket stowage locations, escape routes, emergency exits, and safety equipment positions throughout the vessel.</p><ul class="mb-8 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Universally Recognized IMO Design:</strong> Standardized symbols communicate clearly to multilingual crews and passengers without relying on text or language</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">SOLAS & ISM Code Mandatory:</strong> Required at muster stations, life-saving appliance locations, escape routes, emergency exits, and hazardous areas throughout the vessel</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Photoluminescent Options Available:</strong> Glow-in-the-dark versions remain clearly visible during power blackouts and smoke-filled emergency conditions</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Durable Marine-Grade Materials:</strong> UV, saltwater, and humidity resistant construction suitable for outdoor deck and below-deck installation</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Multiple Sign Categories Available:</strong> Covers life-saving appliance signs, evacuation route signs, prohibition signs, warning signs, and mandatory action signs</li></ul><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Ideal Applications</h2><ul class="mb-8 space-y-2 text-slate-700 list-disc list-inside"><li>Muster station and assembly point identification</li><li>Life jacket, immersion suit, and lifebuoy stowage location marking</li><li>Escape route and emergency exit directional signage</li><li>Prohibition and warning signs in hazardous areas</li><li>SOLAS compliance signage for port state and flag state inspections</li></ul>',            ],
            [
                'name'        => 'IMO Fire Control and Symbol',
                'category'    => 'Navigation & Instruments',
                'image'       => '/images/products/fire-control-symbol.png',
               'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>IMO Fire Control Symbols. Standardized Fire Safety Signage and Fire Control Plan Symbols for SOLAS Compliance.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>IMO Fire Control Symbols</strong> are internationally standardized graphical symbols used to identify and mark fire safety equipment, fire detection systems, fixed fire suppression systems, and fire control stations throughout a vessel. Published by the International Maritime Organization (IMO) under Resolution A.654(16), these symbols form the internationally recognized visual language of a vessel\'s <strong>Fire Control Plan</strong> — the mandatory plan that shows the location of every fire safety system and piece of equipment aboard — and are posted throughout the vessel at the corresponding equipment locations for rapid crew identification during fire emergencies.</p><div class="my-8 bg-cyan-700 text-white rounded-xl p-6 flex gap-4 items-start"><div class="text-3xl mt-1">🗺️</div><div><h3 class="text-base font-bold mb-1">Fire Control Plan Symbols</h3><p class="text-cyan-100 text-sm leading-relaxed">Under SOLAS Chapter II-2, every vessel must carry a <strong class="text-white">Fire Control Plan</strong> showing the layout of each deck with the location of fire detection systems, fixed suppression systems, fire dampers, fire doors, fire extinguishers, fire hose stations, and emergency stops. IMO Fire Control Symbols are the standardized icons used on this plan — and posted at equipment locations — so that <strong class="text-white">any crew member of any nationality</strong> can instantly identify fire equipment and systems without reading text.</p></div></div><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Symbol Categories Covered</h2><ul class="mb-12 space-y-2 text-slate-700"><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Fire Detection & Alarm Systems:</strong> Smoke detectors, heat detectors, manual call points, alarm panels, and fire alarm sounders</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Fixed Fire Suppression Systems:</strong> CO₂ systems, sprinkler systems, foam systems, and dry powder systems</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Portable Fire Extinguishers:</strong> CO₂, dry powder, foam, and water extinguisher location markers</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Fire Hose Stations & Equipment:</strong> Fire hose cabinets, hydrants, nozzles, and breathing apparatus stowage</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Fire Control Boundaries:</strong> Fire doors, fire dampers, watertight doors, and A/B class division markings</li><li class="pl-6 py-1.5 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 bg-slate-50/50"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Emergency Controls:</strong> Fuel shutoff valves, ventilation stops, and emergency power isolation points</li></ul><h2 class="mt-12 mb-6 text-xl font-semibold text-cyan-600">Ideal Applications</h2><ul class="mb-8 space-y-2 text-slate-700 list-disc list-inside"><li>Fire Control Plan preparation and display on passenger and cargo vessels</li><li>Fire equipment location marking throughout the vessel</li><li>Engine room, accommodation, and cargo hold fire safety signage</li><li>Fire station identification and equipment labelling</li><li>SOLAS Chapter II-2 and flag state fire safety compliance</li></ul><div class="mt-10 bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">📋 SOLAS Requirement</strong>Under <strong>SOLAS Chapter II-2 Regulation 15</strong>, a Fire Control Plan using IMO-standardized symbols must be permanently displayed on the vessel and made available to shore-side fire brigades. A duplicate copy must be stored in a weathertight container outside the deckhouse for shore-side fire fighter reference.</div>',
