            [
                'name'        => 'Emergency Position Indicating Radio Beacon',
                'category'    => 'Navigation & Instruments',
                'image'       => '/images/products/position-indicating-symbol.png',
                'description' => '<p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed"><strong>Emergency Position Indicating Radio Beacon NEB-1000. Automatic 406 MHz EPIRB with Built-In GPS for Global Distress Alerting.</strong></p><p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">The <strong>NEB-1000 EPIRB</strong> is a GMDSS-compliant Emergency Position Indicating Radio Beacon that automatically transmits a distress signal on <strong>406.040 MHz</strong> to the international Cospas-Sarsat satellite system the moment it is activated. Equipped with a <strong>built-in 50-channel GPS receiver</strong>, a <strong>121.5 MHz homer</strong> for final approach guidance, and an automatic hydrostatic release, it is the most critical piece of survival electronics carried aboard a vessel. Waterproof to 10 m and buoyant for float-free deployment.</p><div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-3 mb-12"><div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-cyan-400 bg-cyan-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xl font-bold text-cyan-700">406 MHz</div><div class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Distress Frequency</div></div><div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-cyan-400 bg-cyan-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xl font-bold text-cyan-700">48 h</div><div class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Operating Time</div><div class="text-slate-400 text-xs mt-1">at -20°C</div></div><div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-cyan-400 bg-cyan-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xl font-bold text-cyan-700">50 ch</div><div class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">GPS Channels</div></div><div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-cyan-400 bg-cyan-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xl font-bold text-cyan-700">10 m</div><div class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Waterproof Depth</div></div></div><div class="my-8 bg-cyan-700 text-white rounded-xl p-6 flex gap-4 items-start"><div class="text-3xl mt-1">🛰️</div><div><h3 class="text-base font-bold mb-1">How the NEB-1000 EPIRB Works</h3><p class="text-cyan-100 text-sm leading-relaxed">When activated — manually or automatically via the hydrostatic release unit at 1.5–4 m depth — the EPIRB transmits a <strong class="text-white">coded 406 MHz distress signal</strong> to Cospas-Sarsat satellites, relayed to the relevant Maritime Rescue Coordination Centre (MRCC). The built-in GPS provides a <strong class="text-white">precise position fix</strong> that dramatically reduces search area and rescue response time. The 121.5 MHz homer guides rescue craft to the exact location for final recovery.</p></div></div><div class="mb-12 rounded-xl overflow-hidden border border-slate-200"><div class="grid grid-cols-2 bg-cyan-600 text-white text-sm font-semibold px-4 py-3"><div>Specification</div><div>Details</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-white border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Model</div><div>NEB-1000</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-slate-50 border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Case Material</div><div>Special ABS + PC</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-white border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Waterproof</div><div>10 min at 10 m depth</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-slate-50 border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Deployment</div><div>Automatic Hydrostatic Release</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-white border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Weight / Dimensions</div><div>1.35 kg / 692 × 116 mm</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-slate-50 border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">406 MHz Frequency</div><div>406.040 MHz / 5W ± 2 dB</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-white border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">121.5 MHz Homer</div><div>121.5 MHz / 5 mW +3 dB</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-slate-50 border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">GPS</div><div>Built-in, L1-1575.42 MHz, 50 ch</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-white border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Battery</div><div>Lithium, 14.4V (4 × 3.6V)</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-slate-50 border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Operating Time</div><div>48 hours at -20°C</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-white border-b border-slate-100 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Operating Temperature</div><div>-20°C ~ +55°C</div></div><div class="grid grid-cols-2 px-4 py-3 bg-slate-50 text-sm text-slate-700"><div class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Storage Temperature</div><div>-30°C ~ +70°C</div></div></div><div class="mt-10 bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 text-sm text-amber-800 leading-relaxed"><strong class="block font-bold mb-1">⚠️ Important Notice</strong>The EPIRB must be <strong>registered with the appropriate national EPIRB registry</strong> using the vessel\'s MMSI before deployment — an unregistered EPIRB cannot be linked to a vessel identity and will significantly delay rescue response. Check battery and HRU expiry dates at every annual inspection. <strong>Do not test by activating the 406 MHz transmission</strong> — unauthorized transmissions are illegal and will trigger a rescue response.</div>',
